  "description": "The Hubble parameter H(t)H(t) is the rate of cosmic expansion at a given time, defined as the ratio of the rate of change of the scale factor to the scale factor itself:\nH(t)=a˙(t)a(t)H(t) = \\frac{\\dot{a}(t)}{a(t)}Its present-day value, H0H_0, is called the Hubble constant, though it is constant only in the sense that it is evaluated at the current epoch \u0026ndash; the Hubble parameter changes over cosmic time.\nH0H_0 sets the relationship between a galaxy\u0026rsquo;s distance and its recession velocity: v=H0dv = H_0 d. This is Hubble\u0026rsquo;s law. The current best measurements place H0H_0 at approximately 67-73 km/s/Mpc (kilometers per second per megaparsec), meaning that for every megaparsec (about 3.26 million light-years) of distance, the recession velocity increases by 67-73 km/s.\n",
